# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: automata-formal-languages
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Automata theory is closely related to formal language theory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] In this context, automata are used as finite representations of formal languages that may be infinite.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Automata are often classified by the class of formal languages they can recognize, as in the Chomsky hierarchy, which describes a nesting relationship between major classes of automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Automata play a major role in the theory of computation, compiler construction, artificial intelligence, parsing and formal verification.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The theory of abstract automata was developed in the mid-20th century in connection with finite automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Automata theory was initially considered a branch of mathematical systems theory, studying the behavior of discrete-parameter systems.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Early work in automata theory differed from previous work on systems by using abstract algebra to describe information systems rather than differential calculus to describe material systems.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The theory of the finite-state transducer was developed under different names by different research communities.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The earlier concept of Turing machine was also included in the discipline along with new forms of infinite-state automata, such as pushdown automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] 1956 saw the publication of *Automata Studies*, which collected work by scientists including Claude Shannon, W.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Ross Ashby, John von Neumann, Marvin Minsky, Edward F.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] With the publication of this volume, "automata theory emerged as a relatively autonomous discipline".
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The book included Kleene's description of the set of regular events, or regular languages, and a relatively stable measure of complexity in Turing machine programs by Shannon.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] In the same year, Noam Chomsky described the Chomsky hierarchy, a correspondence between automata and formal grammars, and Ross Ashby published *An Introduction to Cybernetics*, an accessible textbook explaining automata and information using basic set theory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The study of linear bounded automata led to the Myhill–Nerode theorem, which gives a necessary and sufficient condition for a formal language to be regular, and an exact count of the number of states in a minimal machine for the language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The pumping lemma for regular languages, also useful in regularity proofs, was proven in this period by Michael O.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Rabin and Dana Scott, along with the computational equivalence of deterministic and nondeterministic finite automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] In the 1960s, a body of algebraic results known as "structure theory" or "algebraic decomposition theory" emerged, which dealt with the realization of sequential machines from smaller machines by interconnection.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] While any finite automaton can be simulated using a universal gate set, this requires that the simulating circuit contain loops of arbitrary complexity.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Structure theory deals with the "loop-free" realizability of machines.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The theory of computational complexity also took shape in the 1960s.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] By the end of the decade, automata theory came to be seen as "the pure mathematics of computer science".
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] What follows is a general definition of an automaton, which restricts a broader definition of a system to one viewed as acting in discrete time-steps, with its state behavior and outputs defined at each step by unchanging functions of only its state and input.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] An automaton *runs* when it is given some sequence of *inputs* in discrete (individual) *time steps* (or just *steps*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] An automaton processes one input picked from a set of *symbols* or *letters*, which is called an *input alphabet*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The symbols received by the automaton as input at any step are a sequence of symbols called *words*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] At each moment during a run of the automaton, the automaton is *in* one of its states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] When the automaton receives new input, it moves to another state (or *transitions*) based on a *transition function* that takes the previous state and current input symbol as parameters.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] At the same time, another function called the *output function* produces symbols from the *output alphabet*, also according to the previous state and current input symbol.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The automaton reads the symbols of the input word and transitions between states until the word is read completely, if it is finite in length, at which point the automaton *halts*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] A state at which the automaton halts is called the *final state*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] To investigate the possible state/input/output sequences in an automaton using formal language theory, a machine can be assigned a *starting state* and a set of *accepting states*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Then, depending on whether a run starting from the starting state ends in an accepting state, the automaton can be said to *accept* or *reject* an input sequence.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The set of all the words accepted by an automaton is called the *language recognized by the automaton*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] A familiar example of a machine recognizing a language is an electronic lock, which accepts or rejects attempts to enter the correct code.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] to describe the machine's behavior when fed whole input words.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] are the set of languages that are recognized by some automaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] For different types of automata, the recognizable languages are different.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Automata are defined to study useful machines under mathematical formalism.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] So the definition of an automaton is open to variations according to the "real world machine" that we want to model using the automaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] People have studied many variations of automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The following are some popular variations in the definition of different components of automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Different combinations of the above variations produce many classes of automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Automata theory is a subject matter that studies properties of various types of automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] For example, the following questions are studied about a given type of automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The following is an incomplete list of types of automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Normally automata theory describes the states of abstract machines but there are discrete automata, analog automata or continuous automata, or hybrid discrete-continuous automata, which use digital data, analog data or continuous time, or digital *and* analog data, respectively.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The following is an incomplete hierarchy in terms of powers of different types of virtual machines.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The hierarchy reflects the nested categories of languages the machines are able to accept.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Each model in automata theory plays important roles in several applied areas.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Finite automata are used in text processing, compilers, and hardware design.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Context-free grammar (CFGs) are used in programming languages and artificial intelligence.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Originally, CFGs were used in the study of human languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Cellular automata are used in the field of artificial life, the most famous example being John Conway's Game of Life.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Some other examples which could be explained using automata theory in biology include mollusk and pine cone growth and pigmentation patterns.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Going further, a theory suggesting that the whole universe is computed by some sort of a discrete automaton, is advocated by some scientists.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The idea originated in the work of Konrad Zuse, and was popularized in America by Edward Fredkin.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Automata also appear in the theory of finite fields: the set of irreducible polynomials that can be written as composition of degree two polynomials is in fact a regular language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Another problem for which automata can be used is the induction of regular languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Automata simulators are pedagogical tools used to teach, learn and research automata theory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] An automata simulator takes as input the description of an automaton and then simulates its working for an arbitrary input string.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The description of the automaton can be entered in several ways.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] An automaton can be defined in a symbolic language or its specification may be entered in a predesigned form or its transition diagram may be drawn by clicking and dragging the mouse.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Well known automata simulators include Turing's World, JFLAP, VAS, TAGS and SimStudio.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] One can define several distinct categories of automata following the automata classification into different types described in the previous section.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] The mathematical category of deterministic automata, sequential machines or *sequential automata*, and Turing machines with *automata homomorphisms* defining the arrows between automata is a Cartesian closed category, it has both categorical limits and colimits.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] An automata homomorphism maps a quintuple of an automaton *A**i* onto the quintuple of another automaton *A**j*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Automata homomorphisms can also be considered as *automata transformations* or as semigroup homomorphisms, when the state space, ***S***, of the automaton is defined as a semigroup **S**g.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Monoids are also considered as a suitable setting for automata in monoidal categories.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] One could also define a *variable automaton*, in the sense of Norbert Wiener in his book on *The Human Use of Human Beings* *via* the endomorphisms $A_{i}\to A_{i}$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Then one can show that such variable automata homomorphisms form a mathematical group.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] In the case of non-deterministic, or other complex kinds of automata, the latter set of endomorphisms may become, however, a *variable automaton groupoid*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Therefore, in the most general case, categories of variable automata of any kind are categories of groupoids or groupoid categories.
[src:automata-formal-languages/automata-theory] Moreover, the category of reversible automata is then a 2-category, and also a subcategory of the 2-category of groupoids, or the groupoid category.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] The **Chomsky hierarchy** in the fields of formal language theory, computer science, and linguistics, is a containment hierarchy of classes of formal grammars.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] A formal grammar describes how to form strings from a formal language's alphabet that are valid according to the language's syntax.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] The linguist Noam Chomsky theorized that four different classes of formal grammars existed that could generate increasingly complex languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Each class can also completely generate the language of all inferior classes (set inclusive).
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] The general idea of a hierarchy of grammars was first described by Noam Chomsky in "Three models for the description of language" during the formalization of transformational-generative grammar (TGG).
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Marcel-Paul Schützenberger also played a role in the development of the theory of formal languages; the paper "The algebraic theory of context free languages" describes the modern hierarchy, including context-free grammars.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Independently, alongside linguists, mathematicians were developing models of computation (via automata).
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Parsing a sentence in a language is similar to computation, and the grammars described by Chomsky proved to both resemble and be equivalent in computational power to various machine models.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] The following table summarizes each of Chomsky's four types of grammars, the class of language it generates, the type of automaton that recognizes it, and the form its rules must have.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] The classes are defined by the constraints on the productions rules.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Note that the set of grammars corresponding to recursive languages is not a member of this hierarchy; these would be properly between Type-0 and Type-1.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Every regular language is context-free, every context-free language is context-sensitive, every context-sensitive language is recursive and every recursive language is recursively enumerable.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] These are all proper inclusions, meaning that there exist recursively enumerable languages that are not context-sensitive, context-sensitive languages that are not context-free and context-free languages that are not regular.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Type-3 grammars generate the regular languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Such a grammar restricts its rules to a single nonterminal on the left-hand side and a right-hand side consisting of a single terminal, possibly followed by a single nonterminal, in which case the grammar is *right regular*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Alternatively, all the rules can have their right-hand sides consist of a single terminal, possibly *preceded* by a single nonterminal (*left regular*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] However, if left-regular rules and right-regular rules are combined, the language need no longer be regular.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] The rule $S\rightarrow \varepsilon$ is also allowed here if S does not appear on the right side of any rule.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] These languages are exactly all languages that can be decided by a finite-state automaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Additionally, this family of formal languages can be obtained by regular expressions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Regular languages are commonly used to define search patterns and the lexical structure of programming languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] For example, the regular language $L=\{a^{n}\mid n>0\}$ is generated by the Type-3 grammar $G=(\{S\},\{a\},P,S)$ with the productions P being the following.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] In linguistics, a language that is not regular is called **supra-regular**.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Type-2 grammars generate the context-free languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] These are defined by rules of the form $A\rightarrow \alpha$ with A being a nonterminal and $\alpha$ being a string of terminals and/or nonterminals.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] These languages are exactly all languages that can be recognized by a non-deterministic pushdown automaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Context-free languages—or rather its subset of deterministic context-free languages—are the theoretical basis for the phrase structure of most programming languages, though their semantic analysis includes context-sensitive name resolution due to declarations and scope.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Often a subset of grammars is used to make parsing easier, such as by an LL parser.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] For example, the context-free language $L=\{a^{n}b^{n}\mid n>0\}$ is generated by the Type-2 grammar $G=(\{S\},\{a,b\},P,S)$ with the productions P being the following.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] The language is context-free but not regular (by the pumping lemma for regular languages).
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Every context-free language can be generated by a grammar in Chomsky normal form.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Type-1 grammars generate context-sensitive languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] These grammars have rules of the form $\alpha A\beta \rightarrow \alpha \gamma \beta$ with A a nonterminal and $\alpha$ , $\beta$ and $\gamma$ strings of terminals and/or nonterminals.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] The strings $\alpha$ and $\beta$ may be empty, but $\gamma$ must be nonempty.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] The rule $S\rightarrow \epsilon$ is allowed if S does not appear on the right side of any rule.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] For example, the context-sensitive language $L=\{a^{n}b^{n}c^{n}\mid n>0\}$ is generated by the Type-1 grammar $G=(\{S,A,B,C,W,Z\},\{a,b,c\},P,S)$ with the productions P being the following.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] The language is context-sensitive but not context-free (by the pumping lemma for context-free languages).
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] A proof that this grammar generates $L=\{a^{n}b^{n}c^{n}\mid n>0\}$ is sketched in the article on Context-sensitive grammars.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Type-0 grammars include all formal grammars.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] There are no constraints on the productions rules.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] They generate exactly all languages that can be recognized by a Turing machine, thus any language that is possible to be generated can be generated by a Type-0 grammar.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] These languages are also known as the *recursively enumerable* or *Turing-recognizable* languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] Note that this is different from the recursive languages, which can be *decided* by an always-halting Turing machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] When researching the position of natural language in the Chomsky hierarchy, it has been shown in the 1950s that natural language is not regular.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] For instance, English contains center embedding constructions, which means that it cannot be regular.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] is not regular, which can be shown using the pumping lemma for context-free languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/chomsky-hierarchy] In subsequent decades, it was shown that natural language is also not context-free, using the example of cross-serial dependencies in Swiss German.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] *Deterministic* refers to the uniqueness of the computation run.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] In search of the simplest models to capture finite-state machines, Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts were among the first researchers to introduce a concept similar to finite automata in 1943.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The figure illustrates a deterministic finite automaton using a state diagram.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] In this example automaton, there are three states: S0, S1, and S2 (denoted graphically by circles).
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The automaton takes a finite sequence of 0s and 1s as input.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] For each state, there is a transition arrow leading out to a next state for both 0 and 1.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Upon reading a symbol, a DFA jumps *deterministically* from one state to another by following the transition arrow.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] For example, if the automaton is currently in state S0 and the current input symbol is 1, then it deterministically jumps to state S1.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA has a *start state* (denoted graphically by an arrow coming in from nowhere) where computations begin, and a set of *accept states* (denoted graphically by a double circle) which help define when a computation is successful.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA is defined as an abstract mathematical concept, but is often implemented in hardware and software for solving various specific problems such as lexical analysis and pattern matching.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] For example, a DFA can model software that decides whether or not online user input such as email addresses are syntactically valid.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs have been generalized to *nondeterministic finite automata (NFA)* which may have several arrows of the same label starting from a state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Using the powerset construction method, every NFA can be translated to a DFA that recognizes the same language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs, and NFAs as well, recognize exactly the set of regular languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Let *w* = *a*1*a*2...*an* be a string over the alphabet Σ.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] In words, the first condition says that the machine starts in the start state *q*0.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The second condition says that given each character of string w, the machine will transition from state to state according to the transition function δ.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The last condition says that the machine accepts w if the last input of w causes the machine to halt in one of the accepting states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Otherwise, it is said that the automaton *rejects* the string.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The set of strings that M accepts is the language *recognized* by M and this language is denoted by *L*(*M*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] A deterministic finite automaton without accept states and without a starting state is known as a transition system or semiautomaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] For more comprehensive introduction of the formal definition see automata theory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The following example is of a DFA M, with a binary alphabet, which requires that the input contains an even number of 0s.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The state *S*1 represents that there has been an even number of 0s in the input so far, while *S*2 signifies an odd number.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] A 1 in the input does not change the state of the automaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] When the input ends, the state will show whether the input contained an even number of 0s or not.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] If the input did contain an even number of 0s, M will finish in state *S*1, an accepting state, so the input string will be accepted.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The language recognized by M is the regular language given by the regular expression `(1*) (0 (1*) 0 (1*))*`, where `*` is the Kleene star, e.g., `1*` denotes any number (possibly zero) of consecutive ones.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] According to the above definition, deterministic finite automata are always *complete*: they define from each state a transition for each input symbol.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] While this is the most common definition, some authors use the term deterministic finite automaton for a slightly different notion: an automaton that defines *at most* one transition for each state and each input symbol; the transition function is allowed to be partial.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] When no transition is defined, such an automaton halts.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] A **local automaton** is a DFA, not necessarily complete, for which all edges with the same label lead to a single vertex.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Local automata accept the class of local languages, those for which membership of a word in the language is determined by a "sliding window" of length two on the word.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] A **Myhill graph** over an alphabet *A* is a directed graph with vertex set *A* and subsets of vertices labelled "start" and "finish".
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The language accepted by a Myhill graph is the set of directed paths from a start vertex to a finish vertex: the graph thus acts as an automaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The class of languages accepted by Myhill graphs is the class of local languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] When the start state and accept states are ignored, a DFA of n states and an alphabet of size k can be seen as a digraph of n vertices in which all vertices have k out-arcs labeled 1, ..., *k* (a k-out digraph).
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] It is known that when *k* ≥ 2 is a fixed integer, with high probability, the largest strongly connected component (SCC) in such a k-out digraph chosen uniformly at random is of linear size and it can be reached by all vertices.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] It has also been proven that if k is allowed to increase as n increases, then the whole digraph has a phase transition for strong connectivity similar to Erdős–Rényi model for connectivity.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] In a random DFA, the maximum number of vertices reachable from one vertex is very close to the number of vertices in the largest SCC with high probability.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] This is also true for the largest induced sub-digraph of minimum in-degree one, which can be seen as a directed version of 1-core.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] If DFAs recognize the languages that are obtained by applying an operation on the DFA recognizable languages then DFAs are said to be closed under the operation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The DFAs are closed under the following operations.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] For each operation, an optimal construction with respect to the number of states has been determined in state complexity research.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Since DFAs are equivalent to nondeterministic finite automata (NFA), these closures may also be proved using closure properties of NFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] A run of a given DFA can be seen as a sequence of compositions of a very general formulation of the transition function with itself.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] For a given input symbol $a\in \Sigma$ , one may construct a transition function $\delta _{a}:Q\rightarrow Q$ by defining $\delta _{a}(q)=\delta (q,a)$ for all $q\in Q$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] (This trick is called currying.) From this perspective, $\delta _{a}$ "acts" on a state in Q to yield another state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] One may then consider the result of function composition repeatedly applied to the various functions $\delta _{a}$ , $\delta _{b}$ , and so on.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Given a pair of letters $a,b\in \Sigma$ , one may define a new function ${\widehat {\delta }}_{ab}=\delta _{a}\circ \delta _{b}$ , where $\circ$ denotes function composition.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] ${\widehat {\delta }}$ is defined for all words $w\in \Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] A run of the DFA is a sequence of compositions of ${\widehat {\delta }}$ with itself.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Repeated function composition forms a monoid.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] For the transition functions, this monoid is known as the transition monoid, or sometimes the *transformation semigroup*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The construction can also be reversed: given a ${\widehat {\delta }}$ , one can reconstruct a $\delta$ , and so the two descriptions are equivalent.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs are one of the most practical models of computation, since there is a trivial linear time, constant-space, online algorithm to simulate a DFA on a stream of input.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs are equivalent in computing power to nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs).
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] This is because, firstly any DFA is also an NFA, so an NFA can do what a DFA can do.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Also, given an NFA, using the powerset construction one can build a DFA that recognizes the same language as the NFA, although the DFA could have exponentially larger number of states than the NFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, even though NFAs are computationally equivalent to DFAs, the above-mentioned problems are not necessarily solved efficiently also for NFAs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The non-universality problem for NFAs is PSPACE complete since there are small NFAs with shortest rejecting word in exponential size.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA is universal if and only if all states are final states, but this does not hold for NFAs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The Equality, Inclusion and Minimization Problems are also PSPACE complete since they require forming the complement of an NFA which results in an exponential blow up of size.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] On the other hand, finite-state automata are of strictly limited power in the languages they can recognize; many simple languages, including any problem that requires more than constant space to solve, cannot be recognized by a DFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The classic example of a simply described language that no DFA can recognize is bracket or Dyck language, i.e., the language that consists of properly paired brackets such as word "(()())".
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Intuitively, no DFA can recognize the Dyck language because DFAs are not capable of counting: a DFA-like automaton needs to have a state to represent any possible number of "currently open" parentheses, meaning it would need an unbounded number of states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Another simpler example is the language consisting of strings of the form *anbn* for some finite but arbitrary number of *a*'s, followed by an equal number of *b*'s.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Given a set of *positive* words $S^{+}\subset \Sigma ^{*}$ and a set of *negative* words $S^{-}\subset \Sigma ^{*}$ one can construct a DFA that accepts all words from $S^{+}$ and rejects all words from $S^{-}$ : this problem is called *DFA identification* (synthesis, learning).
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] While *some* DFA can be constructed in linear time, the problem of identifying a DFA with the minimal number of states is NP-complete.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The first algorithm for minimal DFA identification has been proposed by Trakhtenbrot and Barzdin and is called the *TB-algorithm*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, the TB-algorithm assumes that all words from $\Sigma$ up to a given length are contained in either $S^{+}\cup S^{-}$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Lang proposed an extension of the TB-algorithm that does not use any assumptions about $S^{+}$ and $S^{-}$ , the *Traxbar* algorithm.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, Traxbar does not guarantee the minimality of the constructed DFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Gold also proposed a heuristic algorithm for minimal DFA identification.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Gold's algorithm assumes that $S^{+}$ and $S^{-}$ contain a *characteristic set* of the regular language; otherwise, the constructed DFA will be inconsistent either with $S^{+}$ or $S^{-}$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Other notable DFA identification algorithms include the RPNI algorithm, the Blue-Fringe evidence-driven state-merging algorithm, and Windowed-EDSM.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Yet another step forward is due to application of SAT solvers by Marjin J.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Verwer: the minimal DFA identification problem is reduced to deciding the satisfiability of a Boolean formula.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Though this approach allows finding the minimal DFA, it suffers from exponential blow-up of execution time when the size of input data increases.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Therefore, Heule and Verwer's initial algorithm has later been augmented with making several steps of the EDSM algorithm prior to SAT solver execution: the DFASAT algorithm.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] This allows reducing the search space of the problem, but leads to loss of the minimality guarantee.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] Another way of reducing the search space has been proposed by Ulyantsev et al. by means of new symmetry breaking predicates based on the breadth-first search algorithm: the sought DFA's states are constrained to be numbered according to the BFS algorithm launched from the initial state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] This approach reduces the search space by $C!$ by eliminating isomorphic automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] The machine always accepts a regular language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/deterministic-finite-automaton] There must exist at least one element of the set F (a **HALT** state) for the language to be nonempty.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] In theoretical computer science, a **finite-state machine** (**FSM**) or **finite-state automaton** (**FSA**, plural: *automata*), **finite automaton**, or simply a **state machine**, is a mathematical model of computation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] It is an abstract machine that can be in exactly one of a finite number of *states* at any given time.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The FSM can change from one state to another in response to some inputs; the change from one state to another is called a *transition*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] An FSM is defined by a list of its states, its initial state, and the inputs that trigger each transition.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are of two types—deterministic finite-state machines and non-deterministic finite-state machines.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] For any non-deterministic finite-state machine, an equivalent deterministic one can be constructed.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The behavior of state machines can be observed in many devices in modern society that perform a predetermined sequence of actions depending on a sequence of events with which they are presented.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The finite-state machine has less computational power than some other models of computation such as the Turing machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The computational power distinction means there are computational tasks that a Turing machine can do but an FSM cannot.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] This is because an FSM's memory is limited by the number of states it has.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine has the same computational power as a Turing machine that is restricted such that its head may only perform "read" operations, and always has to move from left to right.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] FSMs are studied in the more general field of automata theory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] An example of a simple mechanism that can be modeled by a state machine is a turnstile.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] A turnstile, used to control access to subways and amusement park rides, is a gate with three rotating arms at waist height, one across the entryway.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Initially the arms are locked, blocking the entry, preventing patrons from passing through.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Depositing a coin or token in a slot on the turnstile unlocks the arms, allowing a single customer to push through.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] After the customer passes through, the arms are locked again until another coin is inserted.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Considered as a state machine, the turnstile has two possible states: *Locked* and *Unlocked*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] There are two possible inputs that affect its state: putting a coin in the slot (*coin*) and pushing the arm (*push*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] In the locked state, pushing on the arm has no effect; no matter how many times the input *push* is given, it stays in the locked state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Putting a coin in – that is, giving the machine a *coin* input – shifts the state from *Locked* to *Unlocked*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] In the unlocked state, putting additional coins in has no effect; that is, giving additional *coin* inputs does not change the state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] A customer pushing through the arms gives a *push* input and resets the state to *Locked*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The turnstile state machine can also be represented by a directed graph called a state diagram *(above)*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Each state is represented by a node (*circle*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Edges (*arrows*) show the transitions from one state to another.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Each arrow is labeled with the input that triggers that transition.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] An input that doesn't cause a change of state (such as a *coin* input in the *Unlocked* state) is represented by a circular arrow returning to the original state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The arrow into the *Locked* node from the black dot indicates it is the initial state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] A *state* is a description of the status of a system that is waiting to execute a *transition*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] A transition is a set of actions to be executed when a condition is fulfilled or when an event is received.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] For example, when using an audio system to listen to the radio (the system is in the "radio" state), receiving a "next" stimulus results in moving to the next station.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] When the system is in the "CD" state, the "next" stimulus results in moving to the next track.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Identical stimuli trigger different actions depending on the current state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Several state-transition table types are used.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The most common representation is shown below: the combination of current state (e.g.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] By itself, the table cannot completely describe the action, so it is common to use footnotes.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Other related representations may not have this limitation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] For example, an FSM definition including the full action's information is possible using state tables (see also virtual finite-state machine).
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The Unified Modeling Language has a notation for describing state machines.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] UML state machines overcome the limitations of traditional finite-state machines while retaining their main benefits.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] UML state machines introduce the new concepts of hierarchically nested states and orthogonal regions, while extending the notion of actions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] UML state machines have the characteristics of both Mealy machines and Moore machines.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] They support actions that depend on both the state of the system and the triggering event, as in Mealy machines, as well as entry and exit actions, which are associated with states rather than transitions, as in Moore machines.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] SDL embeds basic data types called "Abstract Data Types", an action language, and an execution semantic in order to make the finite-state machine executable.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] There are a large number of variants to represent an FSM such as the one in figure 3.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] In addition to their use in modeling reactive systems presented here, finite-state machines are significant in many different areas, including electrical engineering, linguistics, computer science, philosophy, biology, mathematics, video game programming, and logic.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are a class of automata studied in automata theory and the theory of computation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] In computer science, finite-state machines are widely used in modeling of application behavior (control theory), design of hardware digital systems, software engineering, compilers, network protocols, and computational linguistics.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines can be subdivided into acceptors, classifiers, transducers and sequencers.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] A (possibly infinite) set of symbol sequences, called a formal language, is a regular language if there is some acceptor that accepts *exactly* that set.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] For example, the set of binary strings with an even number of zeroes is a regular language (cf.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] 5), while the set of all strings whose length is a prime number is not.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] An acceptor could also be described as defining a language that would contain every string accepted by the acceptor but none of the rejected ones; that language is *accepted* by the acceptor.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] By definition, the languages accepted by acceptors are the regular languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The problem of determining the language accepted by a given acceptor is an instance of the algebraic path problem—itself a generalization of the shortest path problem to graphs with edges weighted by the elements of an (arbitrary) semiring.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] An example of an accepting state appears in Fig.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] 5: a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that detects whether the binary input string contains an even number of 0s.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The FSM uses only entry actions, i.e., output depends only on state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The advantage of the Moore model is a simplification of the behaviour.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The state machine recognizes two commands: "command_open" and "command_close", which trigger state changes.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The entry action (E:) in state "Opening" starts a motor opening the door, the entry action in state "Closing" starts a motor in the other direction closing the door.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] States "Opened" and "Closed" stop the motor when fully opened or closed.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] They signal to the outside world (e.g., to other state machines) the situation: "door is open" or "door is closed".
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The FSM also uses input actions, i.e., output depends on input and state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The use of a Mealy FSM leads often to a reduction of the number of states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] There are two input actions (I:): "start motor to close the door if command_close arrives" and "start motor in the other direction to open the door if command_open arrives".
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The "opening" and "closing" intermediate states are not shown.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] A further distinction is between *deterministic* (DFA) and *non-deterministic* (NFA, GNFA) automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] In a deterministic automaton, every state has exactly one transition for each possible input.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] In a non-deterministic automaton, an input can lead to one, more than one, or no transition for a given state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The powerset construction algorithm can transform any nondeterministic automaton into a (usually more complex) deterministic automaton with identical functionality.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with only one state is called a "combinatorial FSM".
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] It only allows actions upon transition *into* a state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] This concept is useful in cases where a number of finite-state machines are required to work together, and when it is convenient to consider a purely combinatorial part as a form of FSM to suit the design tools.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] There are other sets of semantics available to represent state machines.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] For example, there are tools for modeling and designing logic for embedded controllers.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] They combine hierarchical state machines (which usually have more than one current state), flow graphs, and truth tables into one language, resulting in a different formalism and set of semantics.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] These charts, like Harel's original state machines, support hierarchically nested states, orthogonal regions, state actions, and transition actions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] In accordance with the general classification, the following formal definitions are found.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] For both deterministic and non-deterministic FSMs, it is conventional to allow $\delta$ to be a partial function, i.e. $\delta (s,x)$ does not have to be defined for every combination of $s\in S$ and $x\in \Sigma$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] If an FSM M is in a state s , the next symbol is x and $\delta (s,x)$ is not defined, then M can announce an error (i.e. reject the input).
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] This is useful in definitions of general state machines, but less useful when transforming the machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Some algorithms in their default form may require total functions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] That is, each formal language accepted by a finite-state machine is accepted by such a kind of restricted Turing machine, and vice versa.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends on the state and input symbol ( $\omega :S\times \Sigma \rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Mealy model*, and can be modelled as a Mealy machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends only on the state ( $\omega :S\rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Moore model*, and can be modelled as a Moore machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with no output function at all is known as a semiautomaton or transition system.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] If we disregard the first output symbol of a Moore machine, $\omega (s_{0})$ , then it can be readily converted to an output-equivalent Mealy machine by setting the output function of every Mealy transition (i.e. labeling every edge) with the output symbol given of the destination Moore state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The converse transformation is less straightforward because a Mealy machine state may have different output labels on its incoming transitions (edges).
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Every such state needs to be split in multiple Moore machine states, one for every incident output symbol.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Optimizing an FSM means finding a machine with the minimum number of states that performs the same function.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The fastest known algorithm doing this is the Hopcroft minimization algorithm.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Other techniques include using an implication table, or the Moore reduction procedure.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Additionally, acyclic FSAs can be minimized in linear time.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] In a digital circuit, an FSM may be built using a programmable logic device, a programmable logic controller, logic gates and flip flops or relays.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] More specifically, a hardware implementation requires a register to store state variables, a block of combinational logic that determines the state transition, and a second block of combinational logic that determines the output of an FSM.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] In a *Medvedev machine*, the output is directly connected to the state flip-flops minimizing the time delay between flip-flops and output.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Through state encoding for low power state machines may be optimized to minimize power consumption.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Finite automata are often used in the frontend of programming language compilers.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Such a frontend may comprise several finite-state machines that implement a lexical analyzer and a parser.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] Starting from a sequence of characters, the lexical analyzer builds a sequence of language tokens (such as reserved words, literals, and identifiers) from which the parser builds a syntax tree.
[src:automata-formal-languages/finite-state-machine] The lexical analyzer and the parser handle the regular and context-free parts of the programming language's grammar.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In logic, mathematics, computer science, and linguistics, a **formal language** is a set of strings whose symbols are taken from a set called "alphabet".
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The alphabet of a formal language consists of symbols that concatenate into strings (also called "words").
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Words that belong to a particular formal language are sometimes called *well-formed words*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] A formal language is often defined by means of a formal grammar such as a regular grammar or context-free grammar.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In computer science, formal languages are used, among others, as the basis for defining the grammars of programming languages and controlled natural languages (i.e., formalized versions of subsets of natural languages).
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In computational complexity theory, decision problems are typically defined as formal languages, and complexity classes are defined as the sets of the formal languages that can be parsed by machines with limited computational power.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In logic and the foundations of mathematics, formal languages are used to represent the syntax of axiomatic systems, and mathematical formalism is the philosophy that all of mathematics can be reduced to the syntactic manipulation of formal languages in this way.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The field of **formal language theory** studies primarily the purely syntactic aspects of such languages—that is, their internal structural patterns.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Formal language theory sprang out of linguistics, as a way of understanding the syntactic regularities of natural languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In the 17th century, Gottfried Leibniz imagined and described the characteristica universalis, a universal and formal language which utilised pictographs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Later, Carl Friedrich Gauss investigated the problem of Gauss codes.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In the mid-19th century, George Boole established the field of boolean algebra, which is a formal way of describing logical operations using truth values and set operators.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In his work *An Investigation of The Laws of Thought*, he demonstrated that logical reasoning can be expressed and manipulated through symbolic equations.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Gottlob Frege attempted to realize Leibniz's ideas, through a notational system, first outlined in *Begriffsschrift* (1879) and more fully developed in his 2-volume *Grundgesetze der Arithmetik* (1893/1903).
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In the first half of the 20th century, several developments were made with relevance to formal languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Axel Thue published four papers relating to words and language between 1906 and 1914.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The last of these introduced what Emil Post later termed 'Thue Systems', and gave an early example of an undecidable problem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Post would later use this paper as the basis for a 1947 proof "that the word problem for semigroups was recursively insoluble", and later devised the canonical system for the creation of formal languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In 1907, Leonardo Torres Quevedo introduced a formal language for the description of mechanical drawings (mechanical devices), in Vienna.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] He published "Sobre un sistema de notaciones y símbolos destinados a facilitar la descripción de las máquinas" ("On a system of notations and symbols intended to facilitate the description of machines").
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Heinz Zemanek rated it as an equivalent to a programming language for the numerical control of machine tools.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Noam Chomsky devised an abstract representation of formal and natural languages, known as the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In 1959 John Backus developed the Backus-Naur form to describe the syntax of a high level programming language, following his work in the creation of FORTRAN.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Peter Naur was the secretary/editor for the ALGOL60 Report in which he used Backus–Naur form to describe the Formal part of ALGOL60.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] An *alphabet*, in the context of formal languages, can be any set; its elements are called *letters*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] An alphabet may contain an infinite number of elements; however, most definitions in formal language theory specify alphabets with a finite number of elements, and many results apply only to them.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] It often makes sense to use an alphabet in the usual sense of the word, or more generally any finite character encoding such as ASCII or Unicode.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] A **word** over an alphabet can be any finite sequence (i.e., string) of letters.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The set of all words over an alphabet Σ is usually denoted by Σ* (using the Kleene star).
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The length of a word is the number of letters it is composed of.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] For any alphabet, there is only one word of length 0, the *empty word*, which is often denoted by e, ε, λ or even Λ.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] By concatenation one can combine two words to form a new word, whose length is the sum of the lengths of the original words.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The result of concatenating a word with the empty word is the original word.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In some applications, especially in logic, the alphabet is also known as the *vocabulary* and words are known as *formulas* or *sentences*; this breaks the letter/word metaphor and replaces it by a word/sentence metaphor.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Given a non-empty set $\Sigma$ , a **formal language L over $\Sigma$** is a subset of $\Sigma ^{*}$ , where $\Sigma ^{*}$ is the set of all possible finite-length words over $\Sigma$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] We call the set $\Sigma$ **the alphabet of L**.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] On the other hand, given a formal language L over $\Sigma$ , a word $w\in \Sigma ^{*}$ is *well-formed* if $w\in L$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Similarly, an expression $E\subseteq \Sigma ^{*}$ is *well-formed* if $E\subseteq L$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Sometimes, a formal language L over $\Sigma$ has a set of clear rules and constraints for the creation of all possible well-formed words from $\Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In computer science and mathematics, which do not usually deal with natural languages, the adjective "formal" is often omitted as redundant.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] On the other hand, we can just say "a formal language L " when its alphabet $\Sigma$ is clear in the context.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] While formal language theory usually concerns itself with formal languages that are described by some syntactic rules, the actual definition of the concept "formal language" is only as above: a (possibly infinite) set of finite-length strings composed from a given alphabet, no more and no less.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In practice, there are many languages that can be described by rules, such as regular languages or context-free languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The notion of a formal grammar may be closer to the intuitive concept of a "language", one described by syntactic rules.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] By an abuse of the definition, a particular formal language is often thought of as being accompanied with a formal grammar that describes it.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Under these rules, the string "23+4=555" is in L, but the string "=234=+" is not.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] This formal language expresses natural numbers, well-formed additions, and well-formed addition equalities, but it expresses only what they look like (their syntax), not what they mean (semantics).
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] For instance, nowhere in these rules is there any indication that "0" means the number zero, "+" means addition, "23+4=555" is false, etc.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] For finite languages, one can explicitly enumerate all well-formed words.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] For example, we can describe a language L as just L = {a, b, ab, cba}.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The degenerate case of this construction is the **empty language**, which contains no words at all (L = ∅).
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] However, even over a finite (non-empty) alphabet such as Σ = {a, b} there are an infinite number of finite-length words that can potentially be expressed: "a", "abb", "ababba", "aaababbbbaab", ....
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Therefore, formal languages are typically infinite, and describing an infinite formal language is not as simple as writing *L* = {a, b, ab, cba}.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Formal languages are used as tools in multiple disciplines.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] However, formal language theory rarely concerns itself with particular languages (except as examples), but is mainly concerned with the study of various types of formalisms to describe languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Surprisingly often, the answer to these decision problems is "it cannot be done at all", or "it is extremely expensive" (with a characterization of how expensive).
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Therefore, formal language theory is a major application area of computability theory and complexity theory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Formal languages may be classified in the Chomsky hierarchy based on the expressive power of their generative grammar as well as the complexity of their recognizing automaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Context-free grammars and regular grammars provide a good compromise between expressivity and ease of parsing, and are widely used in practical applications.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Certain operations on languages are common.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] This includes the standard set operations, such as union, intersection, and complement.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Another class of operation is the element-wise application of string operations.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Examples: suppose $L_{1}$ and $L_{2}$ are languages over some common alphabet $\Sigma$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Such string operations are used to investigate closure properties of classes of languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] A class of languages is closed under a particular operation when the operation, applied to languages in the class, always produces a language in the same class again.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] For instance, the context-free languages are known to be closed under union, concatenation, and intersection with regular languages, but not closed under intersection or complement.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The theory of trios and abstract families of languages studies the most common closure properties of language families in their own right.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] are in the language family given by the column).
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] A compiler usually has two distinct components.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] At the most basic conceptual level, a parser, sometimes generated by a parser generator like `yacc`, attempts to decide if the source program is syntactically valid, that is if it is well formed with respect to the programming language grammar for which the compiler was built.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Of course, compilers do more than just parse the source code – they usually translate it into some executable format.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Because of this, a parser usually outputs more than a yes/no answer, typically an abstract syntax tree.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] This is used by subsequent stages of the compiler to eventually generate an executable containing machine code that runs directly on the hardware, or some intermediate code that requires a virtual machine to execute.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In mathematical logic, a *formal theory* is a set of sentences expressed in a formal language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] A *formal system* (also called a *logical calculus*, or a *logical system*) consists of a formal language together with a deductive apparatus (also called a *deductive system*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The deductive apparatus may consist of a set of transformation rules, which may be interpreted as valid rules of inference, or a set of axioms, or have both.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] A formal system is used to derive one expression from one or more other expressions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Although a formal language can be identified with its formulas, a formal system cannot be likewise identified by its theorems.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Two formal systems ${\mathcal {FS}}$ and ${\mathcal {FS'}}$ may have all the same theorems and yet differ in some significant proof-theoretic way (a formula A may be a syntactic consequence of a formula B in one but not another for instance).
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] A *formal proof* or *derivation* is a finite sequence of well-formed formulas (which may be interpreted as sentences, or propositions) each of which is an axiom or follows from the preceding formulas in the sequence by a rule of inference.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The last sentence in the sequence is a theorem of a formal system.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Formal proofs are useful because their theorems can be interpreted as true propositions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] Formal languages are entirely syntactic in nature, but may be given semantics that give meaning to the elements of the language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] For instance, in mathematical logic, the set of possible formulas of a particular logic is a formal language, and an interpretation assigns a meaning to each of the formulas—usually, a truth value.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] The study of interpretations of formal languages is called formal semantics.
[src:automata-formal-languages/formal-language] In mathematical logic, this is often done in terms of model theory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In computability theory, the **halting problem** is the decision problem of determining, from a description of an arbitrary computer program and an input, whether the program will eventually halt (finish running) or continue to run forever.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Alan Turing proved in 1937 that the halting problem is *undecidable*, meaning that no general algorithm exists that can correctly solve the problem for all possible program–input pairs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The problem comes up often in discussions of computability since it demonstrates that some functions are mathematically definable but not computable.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] A key part of the formal statement of the problem is a mathematical definition of a computer and program, usually via a Turing machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The proof then shows, for any program *f* that might determine whether programs halt, that a "pathological" program *g* exists for which *f* makes an incorrect determination.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Specifically, *g* is the program that, when called with some input, passes its own source and its input to *f* and does the opposite of what *f* predicts *g* will do.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The behavior of *f* on *g* shows undecidability as it means no program *f* will solve the halting problem in every possible case.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The halting problem is a decision problem about properties of computer programs on a fixed Turing-complete model of computation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This model of computation includes all programs in Turing-equivalent programming languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Given a program and an input, the question is whether the program will eventually halt when run with that particular input.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In this abstract framework, there are no limitations on the memory or time required for the program's execution; the program may run arbitrarily long and consume arbitrarily large amounts of storage before halting.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] never halts; rather, it goes on forever in an infinite loop.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Simple cases like these are easy to decide, but more complex programs are not.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Turing proved no algorithm exists that always correctly decides whether, for a given arbitrary program and input, the program halts when run with that input.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The essence of Turing's proof is that any such algorithm can be made to produce contradictory output and therefore cannot be correct.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Some infinite loops can be quite useful.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] For instance, event loops are typically coded as infinite loops.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Most subroutines, however, are intended to finish.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In hard real-time computing, subroutines must not only finish, but finish before a given deadline.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In order to meet these requirements, programmers apply the rule of least power and use restricted styles, not quite fully Turing-complete, that make it easy to prove that the resulting subroutines finish before the given deadline.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] These include languages such as MISRA C, SPARK, and Rocq.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The halting problem requires a decision procedure that works for all programs and inputs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] But for any specific program and input, the answer is simply "halts" or "does not halt".
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Consider two simple decision procedures, one that always answers "halts" and another that always answers "does not halt".
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] For any given case, one of these two algorithms answers correctly, yet neither algorithm solves the halting problem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Interpreters are programs that simulate the execution of programs whatever source code they are given.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Such programs can demonstrate that a program does halt, by running the program for some number of steps.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] However, an interpreter will not halt if its input program does not halt, so this approach cannot solve the halting problem as stated; it does not successfully answer "does not halt" for programs that do not halt, or determine whether a program will eventually halt or run forever.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The halting problem is decidable for linear bounded automata (LBAs) or deterministic machines with finite memory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] For nondeterministic finite memory machines, it is also decidable whether the machine halts on none, some, or all of the possible sequences of nondeterministic decisions, by enumerating states after each possible decision.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In April 1936, Alonzo Church published his proof of the undecidability of a problem in the lambda calculus.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Turing's proof was published later, in January 1937.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Since then, many other undecidable problems have been described, including the halting problem which emerged in the 1950s.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Many papers and textbooks refer the definition and proof of undecidability of the halting problem to Turing's 1936 paper.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Turing did not use the terms "halt" or "halting" in any of his published works, including his 1936 paper.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] A search of the academic literature from 1936 to 1958 showed that the first published material using the term "halting problem" was Rogers (1957).
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] However, Rogers says he had a draft of Davis (1958) available to him, and Martin Davis states in the introduction that "the expert will perhaps find some novelty in the arrangement and treatment of topics", so the terminology must be attributed to Davis.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Davis stated in a letter that he had been referring to the halting problem since 1952.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The halting problem is Turing equivalent to both Davis's printing problem ("does a Turing machine starting from a given state ever print a given symbol?") and to the printing problem considered in Turing's 1936 paper ("does a Turing machine starting from a blank tape ever print a given symbol?").
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] However, Turing equivalence is rather loose and does not mean that the two problems are the same.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] There are machines which print but do not halt, and halt but not print.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The printing and halting problems address different issues and exhibit important conceptual and technical differences.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In theoretical computer science, a decision problem is any problem that can be phrased as a yes–no question about a mathematical object.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Given the description of a program (P) and an input (x), does (P(x)) eventually halt?
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The conventional representation of decision problems is the set of objects possessing the property in question.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This set is recursively enumerable, which means there is a computable function that lists all of the pairs (*i*, *x*) it contains.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] However, the complement of this set is not recursively enumerable.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] A decision problem is said to be *decidable* if there exists an algorithm that always halts with the correct answer, and an undecidable problem if no such algorithm exists.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In his original proof Turing formalized the concept of *algorithm* by introducing Turing machines.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] However, the result is in no way specific to them; it applies equally to any other model of computation that is equivalent in its computational power to Turing machines, such as Markov algorithms, Lambda calculus, Post systems, register machines, or tag systems.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] What is important is that the formalization allows a straightforward mapping of algorithms to some data type that the algorithm can operate upon.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The mapping to strings is usually the most straightforward, but strings over an alphabet with *n* characters can also be mapped to numbers by interpreting them as numbers in an *n*-ary numeral system.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] There are many undecidable problems; any set whose Turing degree equals that of the halting problem is such a formulation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Christopher Strachey outlined a proof by contradiction that the halting problem is not solvable.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The proof proceeds as follows: Suppose that there exists a total computable function *halts(f)* that returns true if the subroutine *f* halts (when run with no inputs) and returns false otherwise.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The concept above shows the general method of the proof, but the computable function *halts* does not directly take a subroutine as an argument; instead it takes the source code of a program.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Moreover, the definition of *g* is self-referential.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] A rigorous proof addresses these issues.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Here *program i* refers to the *i* th program in an enumeration of all the programs of a fixed Turing-complete model of computation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Possible values for a total computable function *f* arranged in a 2D array.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The values of *f*(*i*,*i*) and *g*(*i*) are shown at the bottom; *U* indicates that the function *g* is undefined for a particular input value.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The proof proceeds by directly establishing that no total computable function with two arguments can be the required function *h*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Because *g* is partial computable, there must be a program *e* that computes *g*, by the assumption that the model of computation is Turing-complete.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This program is one of all the programs on which the halting function *h* is defined.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The next step of the proof shows that *h*(*e*,*e*) will not have the same value as *f*(*e*,*e*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In either case, *f* cannot be the same function as *h*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Because *f* was an *arbitrary* total computable function with two arguments, all such functions must differ from *h*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This proof is analogous to Cantor's diagonal argument.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] One may visualize a two-dimensional array with one column and one row for each natural number, as indicated in the table above.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The value of *f*(*i*,*j*) is placed at column *i*, row *j*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Because *f* is assumed to be a total computable function, any element of the array can be calculated using *f*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The construction of the function *g* can be visualized using the main diagonal of this array.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] If the array has a 0 at position (*i*,*i*), then *g*(*i*) is 0.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The contradiction comes from the fact that there is some column *e* of the array corresponding to *g* itself.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Now assume *f* was the halting function *h*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Similarly, if *g*(*e*) is not defined, then program *e* does not halt on input *e*, thus *f*(*e,e*) = 0, which leads to *g*(*e*) = 0 under *g'*s construction.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This contradicts the assumption of *g*(*e*) not being defined.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Therefore any arbitrary computable function *f* cannot be the halting function *h*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] A typical method of proving a problem P to be undecidable is to *reduce* the halting problem to P .
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] For example, there cannot be a general algorithm that decides whether a given statement about natural numbers is true or false.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The reason for this is that the proposition stating that a certain program will halt given a certain input can be converted into an equivalent statement about natural numbers.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] If an algorithm could find the truth value of every statement about natural numbers, it could certainly find the truth value of this one; but that would determine whether the original program halts.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Rice's theorem generalizes the theorem that the halting problem is unsolvable.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] It states that for *any* non-trivial property, there is no general decision procedure that, for all programs, decides whether the partial function implemented by the input program has that property.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] (A partial function is a function which may not always produce a result, and so is used to model programs, which can either produce results or fail to halt.) For example, the property "halt for the input 0" is undecidable.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Here, "non-trivial" means that the set of partial functions that satisfy the property is neither the empty set nor the set of all partial functions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] For example, "halt on input 0 within 100 steps" is *not* a property of the partial function that is implemented by the program—it is a property of the program implementing the partial function and is very much decidable.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Gregory Chaitin has defined a halting probability, represented by the symbol Ω, a type of real number that informally is said to represent the probability that a randomly produced program halts.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] These numbers have the same Turing degree as the halting problem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] It is a normal and transcendental number which can be defined but cannot be completely computed.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This means one can prove that there is no algorithm which produces the digits of Ω, although its first few digits can be calculated in simple cases.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Since the negative answer to the halting problem shows that there are problems that cannot be solved by a Turing machine, the Church–Turing thesis limits what can be accomplished by any machine that implements effective methods.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] However, not all machines conceivable to human imagination are subject to the Church–Turing thesis (e.g. oracle machines).
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] It is also an open question whether any such unknown physical processes are involved in the working of the human brain, and whether humans can solve the halting problem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Turing's proof shows that there can be no mechanical, general method (i.e., a Turing machine or a program in some equivalent model of computation) to determine whether algorithms halt.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] However, each individual instance of the halting problem has a definitive answer, which may or may not be practically computable.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Given a specific algorithm and input, one can often show that it halts or does not halt, and in fact computer scientists often do just that as part of a correctness proof.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] There are some heuristics that can be used in an automated fashion to attempt to construct a proof, which frequently succeed on typical programs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This field of research is known as automated termination analysis.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Some results have been established on the theoretical performance of halting problem heuristics, in particular the fraction of programs of a given size that may be correctly classified by a recursive algorithm.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] These results do not give precise numbers because the fractions are uncomputable and also highly dependent on the choice of program encoding used to determine "size".
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] For example, consider classifying programs by their number of states and using a specific "Turing semi-infinite tape" model of computation that errors (without halting) if the program runs off the left side of the tape.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Then $\lim _{n\to \infty }P(x\,{\text{halts is decidable}}\mid x\,{\text{has}}\,n\,{\text{states}})=1$ , over programs x chosen uniformly by number of states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] But this result is in some sense "trivial" because these decidable programs are simply the ones that fall off the tape, and the heuristic is simply to predict not halting due to error.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Thus a seemingly irrelevant detail, namely the treatment of programs with errors, can turn out to be the deciding factor in determining the fraction of programs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] To avoid these issues, several restricted notions of the "size" of a program have been developed.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] For example, a numbering that assigns indices $2^{n}$ to nontrivial programs and all other indices the error state is not dense, but there exists a dense Gödel numbering of syntactically correct Brainfuck programs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] A dense Gödel numbering is called optimal if, for any other Gödel numbering $\alpha$ , there is a 1-1 total recursive function f and a constant c such that for all i , $\alpha _{i}=\phi _{f(i)}$ and $f(i)\leq ci$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This condition ensures that all programs have indices not much larger than their indices in any other Gödel numbering.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Optimal Gödel numberings are constructed by numbering the inputs of a universal Turing machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] A third notion of size uses universal machines operating on binary strings and measures the length of the string needed to describe the input program.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] A universal machine *U* is a machine for which every other machine *V* there exists a total computable function h such that $V(x)=U(h(x))$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] An optimal machine is a universal machine that achieves the Kolmogorov complexity invariance bound, i.e. for every machine *V*, there exists *c* such that for all outputs *x*, if a *V*-program of length *n* outputs *x*, then there exists a *U*-program of at most length $n+c$ outputting *x*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] We consider partial computable functions (algorithms) A .
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The complex nature of these bounds is due to the oscillatory behavior of $\epsilon _{n}(A)$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] There are infrequently occurring new varieties of programs that come in arbitrarily large "blocks", and a constantly growing fraction of repeats.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] If the blocks of new varieties are fully included, the error rate is at least $\epsilon$ , but between blocks the fraction of correctly categorized repeats can be arbitrarily high.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In particular a "tally" heuristic that simply remembers the first N inputs and recognizes their equivalents allows reaching an arbitrarily low error rate infinitely often.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The concepts raised by Gödel's incompleteness theorems are very similar to those raised by the halting problem, and the proofs are quite similar.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In fact, a weaker form of the First Incompleteness Theorem is an easy consequence of the undecidability of the halting problem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This weaker form differs from the standard statement of the incompleteness theorem by asserting that an effective axiomatization of the natural numbers that is both complete and sound is impossible.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The "sound" part is the weakening: it means that we require the axiomatic system in question to prove only *true* statements about natural numbers.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Since soundness implies consistency, this weaker form can be seen as a corollary of the strong form.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] It is important to observe that the statement of the standard form of Gödel's First Incompleteness Theorem is completely unconcerned with the truth value of a statement, but only concerns the issue of whether it is possible to find it through a mathematical proof.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The weaker form of the theorem can be proved from the undecidability of the halting problem as follows.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Assume that we have a sound (and hence consistent) and complete effective axiomatization of all true first-order logic statements about natural numbers.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Then we can build an algorithm that enumerates all these statements.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This means that there is an algorithm *N*(*n*) that, given a natural number *n*, computes a true first-order logic statement about natural numbers, and that for all true statements, there is at least one *n* such that *N*(*n*) yields that statement.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Now suppose we want to decide if the algorithm with representation *a* halts on input *i*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] We know that this statement can be expressed with a first-order logic statement, say *H*(*a*, *i*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Since the axiomatization is complete it follows that either there is an *n* such that *N*(*n*) = *H*(*a*, *i*) or there is an *n′* such that *N*(*n′*) = ¬ *H*(*a*, *i*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] So if we iterate over all *n* until we either find *H*(*a*, *i*) or its negation, we will always halt, and furthermore, the answer it gives us will be true (by soundness).
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This means that this gives us an algorithm to decide the halting problem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Since we know that there cannot be such an algorithm, it follows that the assumption that there is a sound and complete effective axiomatization of all true first-order logic statements about natural numbers must be false.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Many variants of the halting problem can be found in computability textbooks.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Typically, these problems are RE-complete and describe sets of complexity $\Sigma _{1}^{0}$ in the arithmetical hierarchy, the same as the standard halting problem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The variants are thus undecidable, and the standard halting problem reduces to each variant and vice-versa.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] However, some variants have a higher degree of unsolvability and cannot be reduced to the standard halting problem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The *universal halting problem*, also known (in recursion theory) as *totality*, is the problem of determining whether a given computer program will halt *for every input* (the name *totality* comes from the equivalent question of whether the computed function is total).
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This problem is not only undecidable, as the halting problem is, but highly undecidable.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] In terms of the arithmetical hierarchy, it is $\Pi _{2}^{0}$ -complete.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] This means, in particular, that it cannot be decided even with an oracle for the halting problem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] There are many programs that, for some inputs, return a correct answer to the halting problem, while for other inputs they do not return an answer at all.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] However the problem "given program *p*, is it a partial halting solver" (in the sense described) is at least as hard as the halting problem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] To see this, assume that there is an algorithm PHSR ("partial halting solver recognizer") to do that.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] Then it can be used to solve the halting problem, as follows: To test whether input program *x* halts on *y*, construct a program *p* that on input (*x*,*y*) reports *true* and diverges on all other inputs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] A *lossy Turing machine* is a Turing machine in which part of the tape may non-deterministically disappear.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] The halting problem is decidable for a lossy Turing machine but non-primitive recursive.
[src:automata-formal-languages/halting-problem] A machine with an oracle for the halting problem can determine whether particular Turing machines will halt on particular inputs, but they cannot determine, in general, whether machines equivalent to themselves will halt.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] A **nondeterministic finite automaton** (**NFA**), or **nondeterministic finite-state machine**, does not need to obey these restrictions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] In particular, every DFA is also an NFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Sometimes the term **NFA** is used in a narrower sense, referring to an NFA that is *not* a DFA, but not in this article.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Using the subset construction algorithm, each NFA can be translated to an equivalent DFA; i.e., a DFA recognizing the same formal language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Like DFAs, NFAs only recognize regular languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] NFAs were introduced in 1959 by Michael O.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Rabin and Dana Scott, who also showed their equivalence to DFAs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] NFAs are used in the implementation of regular expressions: Thompson's construction is an algorithm for compiling a regular expression to an NFA that can efficiently perform pattern matching on strings.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Conversely, Kleene's algorithm can be used to convert an NFA into a regular expression (whose size is generally exponential in the input automaton).
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] NFAs have been generalized in multiple ways, e.g., nondeterministic finite automata with ε-moves, finite-state transducers, pushdown automata, alternating automata, ω-automata, and probabilistic automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Besides the DFAs, other known special cases of NFAs are unambiguous finite automata (UFA) and self-verifying finite automata (SVFA).
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] There are at least two equivalent ways to describe the behavior of an NFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The first way makes use of the nondeterminism in the name of an NFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] For each input symbol, the NFA transitions to a new state until all input symbols have been consumed.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] In each step, the automaton nondeterministically "chooses" one of the applicable transitions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] If there exists at least one "lucky run", i.e. some sequence of choices leading to an accepting state after completely consuming the input, it is accepted.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Otherwise, i.e. if no choice sequence at all can consume all the input and lead to an accepting state, the input is rejected.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] In the second way, the NFA consumes a string of input symbols, one by one.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] In each step, whenever two or more transitions are applicable, it "clones" itself into appropriately many copies, each one following a different transition.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] If no transition is applicable, the current copy is in a dead end, and it "dies".
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] If, after consuming the complete input, any of the copies is in an accept state, the input is accepted, else, it is rejected.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] For a more elementary introduction of the formal definition, see automata theory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Here, ${\mathcal {P}}(Q)$ denotes the power set of Q .
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Given an NFA $M=(Q,\Sigma ,\delta ,q_{0},F)$ , its recognized language is denoted by $L(M)$ , and is defined as the set of all strings over the alphabet $\Sigma$ that are accepted by M .
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] causes the machine to halt in one of the accepting states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] , it is not required that every state sequence ends in an accepting state, it is sufficient if one does.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The above automaton definition uses a *single initial state*, which is not necessary.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Sometimes, NFAs are defined with a set of initial states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] There is an easy construction that translates an NFA with multiple initial states to an NFA with a single initial state, which provides a convenient notation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The following automaton M, with a binary alphabet, determines if the input ends with a 1.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Since the set $\delta (p,1)$ contains more than one state, M is nondeterministic.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The language of M can be described by the regular language given by the regular expression `(0|1)*1`.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] All possible state sequences for the input string "1011" are shown in the lower picture.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The string is accepted by M since one state sequence satisfies the above definition; it does not matter that other sequences fail to do so.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The feasibility to read the same picture in two ways also indicates the equivalence of both above explanations.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] In contrast, the string "10" is rejected by M (all possible state sequences for that input are shown in the upper right picture), since there is no way to reach the only accepting state, q, by reading the final 0 symbol.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] While q can be reached after consuming the initial "1", this does not mean that the input "10" is accepted; rather, it means that an input string "1" would be accepted.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] A deterministic finite automaton (DFA) can be seen as a special kind of NFA, in which for each state and symbol, the transition function has exactly one state.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Thus, it is clear that every formal language that can be recognized by a DFA can be recognized by an NFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Conversely, for each NFA, there is a DFA such that it recognizes the same formal language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The DFA can be constructed using the powerset construction.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] This result shows that NFAs, despite their additional flexibility, are unable to recognize languages that cannot be recognized by some DFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] It is also important in practice for converting easier-to-construct NFAs into more efficiently executable DFAs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] However, if the NFA has *n* states, the resulting DFA may have up to 2*n* states, which sometimes makes the construction impractical for large NFAs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Nondeterministic finite automaton with ε-moves (NFA-ε) is a further generalization to NFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] In this kind of automaton, the transition function is additionally defined on the empty string ε.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Here, ${\mathcal {P}}(Q)$ denotes the power set of Q and $\varepsilon$ denotes empty string.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] $E(q)$ is known as the **epsilon closure**, (also **ε-closure**) of q .
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The ε-closure of a set P of states of an NFA is defined as the set of states reachable from any state in P following ε-transitions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Formally, for $P\subseteq Q$ , define $E(P)=\bigcup \limits _{q\in P}E(q)$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Similar to NFA without ε-moves, the transition function $\delta$ of an NFA-ε can be extended to strings.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Informally, $\delta ^{*}(q,w)$ denotes the set of all states the automaton may have reached when starting in state $q\in Q$ and reading the string $w\in \Sigma ^{*}.$ The function $\delta ^{*}:Q\times \Sigma ^{*}\rightarrow {\mathcal {P}}(Q)$ can be defined recursively as follows.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Let M be a NFA-ε, with a binary alphabet, that determines if the input contains an even number of 0s or an even number of 1s.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Note that 0 occurrences is an even number of occurrences as well.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] M can be viewed as the union of two DFAs: one with states $\{S_{1},S_{2}\}$ and the other with states $\{S_{3},S_{4}\}$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] We define M using ε-moves but M can be defined without using ε-moves.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] To show NFA-ε is equivalent to NFA, first note that NFA is a special case of NFA-ε, so it remains to show for every NFA-ε, there exists an equivalent NFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] One has to distinguish the transition functions of M and $M',$ viz. $\delta$ and $\delta ',$ and their extensions to strings, $\delta ^{*}$ and $\delta '^{*},$ respectively.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] By construction, $M'$ has no ε-transitions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Since NFA is equivalent to DFA, NFA-ε is also equivalent to DFA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The set of languages recognized by NFAs is closed under the following operations.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] These closure operations are used in Thompson's construction algorithm, which constructs an NFA from any regular expression.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] They can also be used to prove that NFAs recognize exactly the regular languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Since NFAs are equivalent to nondeterministic finite automaton with ε-moves (NFA-ε), the above closures are proved using closure properties of NFA-ε.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The machine starts in the specified initial state and reads in a string of symbols from its alphabet.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The automaton uses the state transition function Δ to determine the next state using the current state, and the symbol just read or the empty string.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] However, "the next state of an NFA depends not only on the current input event, but also on an arbitrary number of subsequent input events.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Until these subsequent events occur it is not possible to determine which state the machine is in".
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] If, when the automaton has finished reading, it is in an accepting state, the NFA is said to accept the string, otherwise it is said to reject the string.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The set of all strings accepted by an NFA is the language the NFA accepts.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] For every NFA a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) can be found that accepts the same language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] Therefore, it is possible to convert an existing NFA into a DFA for the purpose of implementing a (perhaps) simpler machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] This can be performed using the powerset construction, which may lead to an exponential rise in the number of necessary states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] For a formal proof of the powerset construction, please see the Powerset construction article.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] NFAs and DFAs are equivalent in that if a language is recognized by an NFA, it is also recognized by a DFA and vice versa.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] The establishment of such equivalence is important and useful.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] It is useful because constructing an NFA to recognize a given language is sometimes much easier than constructing a DFA for that language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] It is important because NFAs can be used to reduce the complexity of the mathematical work required to establish many important properties in the theory of computation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/nondeterministic-finite-automaton] For example, it is much easier to prove closure properties of regular languages using NFAs than DFAs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In the theory of computation, a branch of theoretical computer science, a **pushdown automaton** (**PDA**) is a type of automaton that employs a stack.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Pushdown automata are used in theories about what can be computed by machines.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] They are more capable than finite-state machines but less capable than Turing machines (see below).
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Deterministic pushdown automata can recognize all deterministic context-free languages while nondeterministic ones can recognize all context-free languages, with the former often used in parser design.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The term "pushdown" refers to the fact that the stack can be regarded as being "pushed down" like a tray dispenser at a cafeteria, since the operations never work on elements other than the top element.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A **stack automaton**, by contrast, does allow access to and operations on deeper elements.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Stack automata can recognize a strictly larger set of languages than pushdown automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A nested stack automaton allows full access, and also allows stacked values to be entire sub-stacks rather than just single finite symbols.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A finite-state machine only considers the input signal and the current state: it has no stack to work with and therefore is unable to access previous values of the input.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] It can only choose a new state, the result of following the transition.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] It can manipulate the stack as part of performing a transition.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A pushdown automaton reads a given input string from left to right.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In each step, it chooses a transition by indexing a table by input symbol, current state, and the symbol at the top of the stack.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A pushdown automaton can also manipulate the stack, as part of performing a transition.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The manipulation can be to push a particular symbol to the top of the stack, or to pop off the top of the stack.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The automaton can alternatively ignore the stack, and leave it as it is.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Put together: Given an input symbol, current state, and stack symbol, the automaton can follow a transition to another state, and optionally manipulate (push or pop) the stack.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] If, in every situation, at most one such transition action is possible, then the automaton is called a **deterministic pushdown automaton (DPDA)**.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In general, if several actions are possible, then the automaton is called a **general**, or **nondeterministic**, **PDA**.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A given input string may drive a nondeterministic pushdown automaton to one of several configuration sequences; if one of them leads to an accepting configuration after reading the complete input string, the latter is said to belong to the *language accepted by the automaton*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] We use standard formal language notation: $\Gamma ^{*}$ denotes the set of finite-length strings over alphabet $\Gamma$ and $\varepsilon$ denotes the empty string.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] An element $(p,a,A,q,\alpha )\in \delta$ is a transition of M .
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] It has the intended meaning that M , in state $p\in Q$ , on the input $a\in \Sigma \cup \{\varepsilon \}$ and with $A\in \Gamma$ as topmost stack symbol, may read a , change the state to q , pop A , replacing it by pushing $\alpha \in \Gamma ^{*}$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The $(\Sigma \cup \{\varepsilon \})$ component of the transition relation is used to formalize that the PDA can either read a letter from the input, or proceed leaving the input untouched.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Here $\delta (p,a,A)$ contains all possible actions in state p with A on the stack, while reading a on the input.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Note that *finite* in this definition is essential.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In order to formalize the semantics of the pushdown automaton, a description of the current situation is introduced.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Any 3-tuple $(p,w,\beta )\in Q\times \Sigma ^{*}\times \Gamma ^{*}$ is called an *instantaneous description* (ID) of M , which includes the current state, the part of the input tape that has not been read, and the contents of the stack (top-most symbol written first).
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The transition relation $\delta$ defines the step-relation $\vdash _{M}$ of M on instantaneous descriptions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] For instruction $(p,a,A,q,\alpha )\in \delta$ there exists a step $(p,ax,A\gamma )\vdash _{M}(q,x,\alpha \gamma )$ , for every $x\in \Sigma ^{*}$ and every $\gamma \in \Gamma ^{*}$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In general, pushdown automata are nondeterministic, meaning that in a given instantaneous description $(p,w,\beta )$ there may be several possible steps.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Any of these steps can be chosen in a computation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] With the above definition, in each step a single symbol (top of the stack) is always popped, and replaced with as many symbols as necessary.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] As a consequence, no step is defined when the stack is empty.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Computations of the pushdown automaton are sequences of steps.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The computation starts in the initial state $q_{0}$ with the initial stack symbol Z on the stack, and a string w on the input tape—thus, with initial description $(q_{0},w,Z)$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The pushdown automaton either accepts by final state, which means that after reading its input the automaton reaches an accepting state (in F ), or else it accepts by empty stack ( $\varepsilon$ ), which means that after reading its input the automaton empties its stack.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The first acceptance mode uses the internal memory (state), the second the external memory (stack).
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Here $\vdash _{M}^{*}$ represents the reflexive and transitive closure of the step relation $\vdash _{M}$ , meaning any number of consecutive steps (zero, one or more).
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] For each single pushdown automaton, these two languages need have no relation; they may be equal, but usually this is not the case.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A specification of the automaton should also include the intended mode of acceptance.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Taken over all pushdown automata, both acceptance conditions define the same family of languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In words, the first two instructions say that in state p any time the symbol 0 is read, one A is pushed onto the stack.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Pushing symbol A on top of another A is formalized as replacing top A by AA (and similarly for pushing symbol A on top of a Z).
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The third and fourth instructions say that, at any moment the automaton may move from state p to state q.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The fifth instruction says that in state q, for each symbol 1 read, one A is popped.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Finally, the sixth instruction says that the machine may move from state q to accepting state r only when Z is the top stack symbol.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In this PDA, that is equivalent to the stack consisting of a single Z, since Z is only used as the bottom-of-stack marker and no transition pushes another Z above it.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] There seems to be no generally used representation for PDA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Here we have depicted the instruction $(p,a,A,q,\alpha )$ by an edge from state p to state q labelled by $a;A/\alpha$ (read a from input string; replace A at top of stack by $\alpha$ ).
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The following illustrates how the above PDA computes on different input strings.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The subscript M from the step symbol $\vdash$ is here omitted.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Every context-free grammar can be transformed into an equivalent nondeterministic pushdown automaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The derivation process of the grammar is simulated in a leftmost way.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Where the grammar rewrites a nonterminal, the PDA takes the topmost nonterminal from its stack and replaces it by the right-hand part of a grammatical rule (*expand*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Where the grammar generates a terminal symbol, the PDA reads a symbol from input when it is the topmost symbol on the stack (*match*).
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In a sense the stack of the PDA contains the unprocessed data of the grammar, corresponding to a pre-order traversal of a derivation tree.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Technically, given a context-free grammar, the PDA has a single state, 1, and its transition relation is constructed as follows.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Its initial stack symbol is the grammar's start symbol.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] For a context-free grammar in Greibach normal form, defining (1,γ) ∈ δ(1,*a*,*A*) for each grammar rule *A* → *a*γ also yields an equivalent nondeterministic pushdown automaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The converse, finding a grammar for a given PDA, is not that easy.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The trick is to code two states of the PDA into the nonterminals of the grammar.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The language of strings accepted by a deterministic pushdown automaton (DPDA) is called a deterministic context-free language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Not all context-free languages are deterministic.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] As a consequence, the DPDA is a strictly weaker variant of the PDA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Even for regular languages, there is a size explosion problem: for any recursive function f and for arbitrarily large integers n , there is a PDA of size n describing a regular language whose smallest DPDA has at least $f(n)$ states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] For many non-regular PDAs, any equivalent DPDA would require an unbounded number of states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A finite automaton with access to two stacks is a more powerful device, equivalent in power to a Turing machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A linear bounded automaton is a device which is more powerful than a pushdown automaton but less so than a Turing machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A pushdown automaton is computationally equivalent to a "restricted" Turing Machine (TM) with two tapes, which is restricted in the following manner.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] On the first tape, the TM can only read the input and move from left to right (i.e., it cannot make changes).
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] That a PDA is weaker than a TM can be boiled down to the fact that the "pop" procedure deletes some data.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In order to make a PDA as strong as a TM, we need to save this lost data somewhere; this can be achieved by introducing a second stack.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In the aforementioned TM model of pushdown automata, this is equivalent to a TM with *three* tapes, wherein the first tape is the read-only input tape, and both the second and third tapes are "push" and "pop" (stack) tapes.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In order for such a PDA to simulate any given TM, we give the input of the PDA to the first tape, while keeping both the stacks empty; it then goes on to push all the input from the input tape onto the first stack.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A generalized pushdown automaton (GPDA) is a PDA that writes an entire string of some known length to the stack or removes an entire string from the stack in one step.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] where $Q,\Sigma \,,\Gamma \,,q_{0}$ , and ⁠ F ⁠ are defined the same way as a PDA.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Computation rules for a GPDA are the same as a PDA except that the $a_{i+1}$ 's and $b_{i+1}$ 's are now strings instead of symbols.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Pushdown automata and generalized pushdown automata are equivalent in that if a language is recognized by a PDA, it is also recognized by a GPDA, and vice versa.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] As a generalization of pushdown automata, Ginsburg, Greibach, and Harrison (1967) investigated **stack automata**, which may additionally step left or right in the input string (surrounded by special endmarker symbols to prevent slipping out), and step up or down in the stack in read-only mode.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] A stack automaton is called *nonerasing* if it never pops from the stack.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The class of languages accepted by nondeterministic, nonerasing stack automata is *NSPACE*(*n*2), which is a superset of the context-sensitive languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The class of languages accepted by deterministic, nonerasing stack automata is *DSPACE*(*n*⋅log(*n*)).
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] States in $Q_{\exists }$ and $Q_{\forall }$ are called *existential* resp.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In an existential state an APDA nondeterministically chooses the next state and accepts if *at least one* of the resulting computations accepts.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] In a universal state APDA moves to all next states and accepts if *all* the resulting computations accept.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] The model was introduced by Chandra, Kozen and Stockmeyer.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Ladner, Lipton and Stockmeyer proved that this model is equivalent to EXPTIME i.e. a language is accepted by some APDA if, and only if, it can be decided by an exponential-time algorithm.
[src:automata-formal-languages/pushdown-automaton] Aizikowitz and Kaminski introduced *synchronized alternating pushdown automata* (SAPDA) that are equivalent to conjunctive grammars in the same way as nondeterministic PDA are equivalent to context-free grammars.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Alternatively, a regular language can be defined as a language recognised by a finite automaton.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] The equivalence of regular expressions and finite automata is known as **Kleene's theorem** (after American mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene).
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] In the Chomsky hierarchy, regular languages are the languages generated by Type-3 grammars.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] See *Regular expression § Formal language theory* for syntax and semantics of regular expressions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] All finite languages are regular; in particular the empty string language {ε} = ∅* is regular.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Other typical examples include the language consisting of all strings over the alphabet {*a*, *b*} which contain an even number of *a*s, or the language consisting of all strings of the form: several *a*s followed by several *b*s.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] A simple example of a language that is not regular is the set of strings {*a**n**b**n* | *n* ≥ 0}.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Intuitively, it cannot be recognized with a finite automaton, since a finite automaton has finite memory and it cannot remember the exact number of a's.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Techniques to prove this fact rigorously are given below.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] 11. the number of equivalence classes of its syntactic congruence is finite.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Properties 10. and 11. are purely algebraic approaches to define regular languages; a similar set of statements can be formulated for a monoid *M* ⊆ Σ*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] In this case, equivalence over *M* leads to the concept of a recognizable language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Some authors use one of the above properties different from "1." as an alternative definition of regular languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Some of the equivalences above, particularly those among the first four formalisms, are called *Kleene's theorem* in textbooks.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Precisely which one (or which subset) is called such varies between authors.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] One textbook calls the equivalence of regular expressions and NFAs ("1." and "2." above) "Kleene's theorem".
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Another textbook calls the equivalence of regular expressions and DFAs ("1." and "3." above) "Kleene's theorem".
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Two other textbooks first prove the expressive equivalence of NFAs and DFAs ("2." and "3.") and then state "Kleene's theorem" as the equivalence between regular expressions and finite automata (the latter said to describe "recognizable languages").
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Other authors simply *define* "rational expression" and "regular expressions" as synonymous and do the same with "rational languages" and "regular languages".
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Apparently, the term *regular* originates from a 1951 technical report where Kleene introduced *regular events* and explicitly welcomed "any suggestions as to a more descriptive term".
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Noam Chomsky, in his 1959 seminal article, used the term *regular* in a different meaning at first (referring to what is called *Chomsky normal form* today), but noticed that his *finite state languages* were equivalent to Kleene's *regular events*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Given two deterministic finite automata *A* and *B*, it is decidable whether they accept the same language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] For regular expressions, the universality problem is NP-complete already for a singleton alphabet.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] For larger alphabets, that problem is PSPACE-complete.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] For a binary alphabet, the theory is called S2S.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] In computational complexity theory, the complexity class of all regular languages is sometimes referred to as **REGULAR** or **REG** and equals DSPACE(O(1)), the decision problems that can be solved in constant space (the space used is independent of the input size).
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] **REGULAR** ≠ **AC**0, since it (trivially) contains the parity problem of determining whether the number of 1 bits in the input is even or odd and this problem is not in **AC**0.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] On the other hand, **REGULAR** does not contain **AC**0, because the nonregular language of palindromes, or the nonregular language $\{0^{n}1^{n}:n\in \mathbb {N} \}$ can both be recognized in **AC**0.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] If a language is *not* regular, it requires a machine with at least Ω(log log *n*) space to recognize (where *n* is the input size).
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] In other words, DSPACE(o(log log *n*)) equals the class of regular languages.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] In practice, most nonregular problems are studied in a setting with at least logarithmic space, as this is the amount of space required to store a pointer into the input tape.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] To locate the regular languages in the Chomsky hierarchy, one notices that every regular language is context-free.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] The converse is not true: for example, the language consisting of all strings having the same number of *a*s as *b*s is context-free but not regular.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] To prove that a language is not regular, one often uses the Myhill–Nerode theorem and the pumping lemma.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Other approaches include using the closure properties of regular languages or quantifying Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Let $s_{L}(n)$ denote the number of words of length n in L .
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] The generating function of a language *L* is a rational function if *L* is regular.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Thus, non-regularity of certain languages $L'$ can be proved by counting the words of a given length in $L'$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Consider, for example, the Dyck language of strings of balanced parentheses.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] The number of words of length $2n$ in the Dyck language is equal to the Catalan number $C_{n}\sim {\frac {4^{n}}{n^{3/2}{\sqrt {\pi }}}}$ , which is not of the form $p(n)\lambda ^{n}$ , witnessing the non-regularity of the Dyck language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Care must be taken since some of the eigenvalues $\lambda _{i}$ could have the same magnitude.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] For example, the number of words of length n in the language of all even binary words is not of the form $p(n)\lambda ^{n}$ , but the number of words of even or odd length are of this form; the corresponding eigenvalues are $2,-2$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] In general, for every regular language there exists a constant d such that for all a , the number of words of length $dm+a$ is asymptotically $C_{a}m^{p_{a}}\lambda _{a}^{m}$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] The zeta function of a regular language is not in general rational, but that of an arbitrary cyclic language is.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] The notion of a regular language has been generalized to infinite words (see ω-automata) and to trees (see tree automaton).
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Rational set generalizes the notion (of regular/rational language) to monoids that are not necessarily free.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Likewise, the notion of a recognizable language (by a finite automaton) has namesake as recognizable set over a monoid that is not necessarily free.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Howard Straubing notes in relation to these facts that “The term "regular language" is a bit unfortunate.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Papers influenced by Eilenberg's monograph often use either the term "recognizable language", which refers to the behavior of automata, or "rational language", which refers to important analogies between regular expressions and rational power series.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Rational series is another generalization, this time in the context of a formal power series over a semiring.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] This approach gives rise to weighted rational expressions and weighted automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] In this algebraic context, the regular languages (corresponding to Boolean-weighted rational expressions) are usually called *rational languages*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/regular-language] Also in this context, Kleene's theorem finds a generalization called the Kleene–Schützenberger theorem.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] A **Turing machine** is a mathematical model of computation describing an abstract machine that manipulates symbols on a strip of tape according to a table of rules.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Despite the model's simplicity, it is capable of implementing any computer algorithm.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The machine operates on an infinite memory tape divided into discrete cells, each of which can hold a single symbol drawn from a finite set of symbols called the alphabet of the machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] It has a "head" that, at any point in the machine's operation, is positioned over one of these cells, and a "state" selected from a finite set of states.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] At each step of its operation, the head reads the symbol in its cell.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Then, based on the symbol and the machine's own present state, the machine writes a symbol into the same cell, and moves the head one step to the left or the right, or halts the computation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The choice of which replacement symbol to write, which direction to move the head, and whether to halt is based on a finite table that specifies what to do for each combination of the current state and the symbol that is read.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] As with a real computer program, it is possible for a Turing machine to go into an infinite loop which will never halt.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The Turing machine was invented in 1936 by Alan Turing, who called it an "a-machine" (automatic machine).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] It was Turing's doctoral advisor, Alonzo Church, who later coined the term "Turing machine" in a review.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Turing machines proved the existence of fundamental limitations on the power of mechanical computation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] While they can express arbitrary computations, their minimalist design makes them too slow for computation in practice: real-world computers are based on different designs that, unlike Turing machines, use random-access memory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Turing completeness is the ability for a model of computation or a system of instructions to simulate a Turing machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] A programming language that is Turing complete is theoretically capable of expressing all tasks accomplishable by computers; nearly all programming languages are Turing complete if the limitations of finite memory are ignored.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] A Turing machine is an idealised model of a central processing unit (CPU) that controls all data manipulation done by a computer, with the canonical machine using sequential memory to store data.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Typically, the sequential memory is represented as a tape of infinite length on which the machine can perform read and write operations.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In the context of formal language theory, a Turing machine (automaton) is capable of enumerating some arbitrary subset of valid strings of an alphabet.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] A set of strings which can be enumerated in this manner is called a recursively enumerable language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The Turing machine can equivalently be defined as a model that recognises valid input strings, rather than enumerating output strings.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Given a Turing machine *M* and an arbitrary string *s*, it is generally not possible to decide whether *M* will eventually produce *s*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] This is due to the fact that the halting problem is unsolvable, which has major implications for the theoretical limits of computing.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] A Turing machine that is able to simulate any other Turing machine is called a universal Turing machine (UTM, or simply a universal machine).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Another mathematical formalism, lambda calculus, with a similar "universal" nature was introduced by Alonzo Church.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Church's work intertwined with Turing's to form the basis for the Church–Turing thesis.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Studying the abstract properties of Turing machines has yielded many insights into computer science, computability theory, and complexity theory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The Turing machine mathematically models a machine that mechanically operates on a tape.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] On this tape are symbols, which the machine can read and write, one at a time, using a tape head.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Operation is fully determined by a finite set of elementary instructions such as "in state 42, if the symbol seen is 0, write a 1; if the symbol seen is 1, change into state 17; in state 17, if the symbol seen is 0, write a 1 and change to state 6"; etc.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Move the head (which is described by dk and can have values: 'L' for one step left *or* 'R' for one step right *or* 'N' for staying in the same place).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Assume the same or a *new state* as prescribed (go to state qi1).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In the 4-tuple models, erasing or writing a symbol (aj1) and moving the head left or right (dk) are specified as separate instructions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The table tells the machine to (ia) erase or write a symbol *or* (ib) move the head left or right, *and then* (ii) assume the same or a new state as prescribed, but not both actions (ia) and (ib) in the same instruction.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In some models, if there is no entry in the table for the current combination of symbol and state, then the machine will halt; other models require all entries to be filled.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] A variant allows "no shift", say N, as a third element of the set of directions $\{L,R\}$ .
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Initially all tape cells are marked with 0 .
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Definitions in literature sometimes differ slightly, to make arguments or proofs easier or clearer, but this is always done in such a way that the resulting machine has the same computational power.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] For example, the set could be changed from $\{L,R\}$ to $\{L,R,N\}$ , where *N* ("None" or "No-operation") would allow the machine to stay on the same tape cell instead of moving left or right.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] This would not increase the machine's computational power.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] For the remainder of this article "definition 1" (the Turing/Davis convention) will be used.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In the following table, Turing's original model allowed only the first three lines that he called N1, N2, N3.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] He allowed for erasure of the "scanned square" by naming a 0th symbol S0 = "erase" or "blank", etc.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] However, he did not allow for non-printing, so every instruction-line includes "print symbol Sk" or "erase".
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Any Turing table (list of instructions) can be constructed from the above nine 5-tuples.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] For technical reasons, the three non-printing or "N" instructions (4, 5, 6) can usually be dispensed with.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] For examples see Turing machine examples.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Less frequently the use of 4-tuples are encountered: these represent a further atomization of the Turing instructions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The word "state" used in context of Turing machines can be a source of confusion, as it can mean two things.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Most commentators after Turing have used "state" to mean the name/designator of the current instruction to be performed—i.e. the contents of the state register.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] But Turing (1936) made a strong distinction between a record of what he called the machine's "m-configuration", and the machine's (or person's) "state of progress" through the computation—the current state of the total system.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Earlier in his paper Turing carried this even further: he gives an example where he placed a symbol of the current "m-configuration" —the instruction's label— beneath the scanned square, together with all the symbols on the tape.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] He calls it "the *complete configuration*".
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] To print the "complete configuration" on one line, he places the state-label/m-configuration to the *left* of the scanned symbol.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] But Kleene refers to "q4" itself as "the machine state".
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Hopcroft and Ullman call this composite the "instantaneous description" and follow the Turing convention of putting the "current state" (instruction-label, m-configuration) to the *left* of the scanned symbol (p.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] 149), that is, the instantaneous description is the composite of non-blank symbols to the left, state of the machine, the current symbol scanned by the head, and the non-blank symbols to the right.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] This means: after three moves the tape has ...
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] 000110000 ... on it, the head is scanning the right-most 1, and the state is *A*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Blanks (in this case represented by "0"s) can be part of the total state as shown here: *B*01; the tape has a single 1 on it, but the head is scanning the 0 ("blank") to its left and the state is *B*.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] To the right: the above table as expressed as a "state transition" diagram.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Usually large tables are better left as tables (Booth, p.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] They are more readily simulated by computer in tabular form (Booth, p.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] However, certain concepts—e.g. machines with "reset" states and machines with repeating patterns (cf.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] 244ff)—can be more readily seen when viewed as a drawing.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Whether a drawing represents an improvement on its table must be decided by the reader for the particular context.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The reader should again be cautioned that such diagrams represent a snapshot of their table frozen in time, *not* the course ("trajectory") of a computation *through* time and space.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] While every time the busy beaver machine "runs" it will always follow the same state-trajectory, this is not true for the "copy" machine that can be provided with variable input "parameters".
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The diagram "progress of the computation" shows the three-state busy beaver's "state" (instruction) progress through its computation from start to finish.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] On the far right is the Turing "complete configuration" (Kleene "situation", Hopcroft–Ullman "instantaneous description") at each step.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] If the machine were to be stopped and cleared to blank both the "state register" and entire tape, these "configurations" could be used to rekindle a computation anywhere in its progress.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Many machines that might be thought to have more computational capability than a simple universal Turing machine can be shown to have no more power (Hopcroft and Ullman p.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] They might compute faster, perhaps, or use less memory, or their instruction set might be smaller, but they cannot compute more powerfully (i.e. more mathematical functions).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] A Turing machine is equivalent to a single-stack pushdown automaton (PDA) that has been made more flexible and concise by relaxing the last-in-first-out (LIFO) requirement of its stack.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In addition, a Turing machine is also equivalent to a two-stack PDA with standard LIFO semantics, by using one stack to model the tape left of the head and the other stack for the tape to the right.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] At the other extreme, some very simple models turn out to be Turing-equivalent, i.e. to have the same computational power as the Turing machine model.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Read-only, right-moving Turing machines are equivalent to DFAs (as well as NFAs by conversion using the NFA to DFA conversion algorithm).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] For practical and didactic intentions, the equivalent register machine can be used as a usual assembly programming language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] A relevant question is whether or not the computation model represented by concrete programming languages is Turing equivalent.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] While the computation of a real computer is based on finite states and thus not capable to simulate a Turing machine, programming languages themselves do not necessarily have this limitation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Kirner et al., 2009 have shown that among the general-purpose programming languages some are Turing complete while others are not.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] For example, ANSI C is not Turing complete, as all instantiations of ANSI C (different instantiations are possible as the standard deliberately leaves certain behaviour undefined for legacy reasons) imply a finite-space memory.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] This is because the size of memory reference data types, called *pointers*, is accessible inside the language.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] However, other programming languages like Pascal do not have this feature, which allows them to be Turing complete in principle.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] It is just Turing complete in principle, as memory allocation in a programming language is allowed to fail, which means the programming language can be Turing complete when ignoring failed memory allocations, but the compiled programs executable on a real computer cannot.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Turing (1936) does not elaborate further except in a footnote in which he describes how to use an a-machine to "find all the provable formulae of the [Hilbert] calculus" rather than use a choice machine.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] He "suppose[s] that the choices are always between two possibilities 0 and 1.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Each proof will then be determined by a sequence of choices i1, i2, ..., in (i1 = 0 or 1, i2 = 0 or 1, ..., in = 0 or 1), and hence the number 2n + i12n-1 + i22n-2 + ... +in completely determines the proof.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] This is indeed the technique by which a deterministic (i.e., a-) Turing machine can be used to mimic the action of a nondeterministic Turing machine; Turing solved the matter in a footnote and appears to dismiss it from further consideration.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] An oracle machine or o-machine is a Turing a-machine that pauses its computation at state "**o**" while, to complete its calculation, it "awaits the decision" of "the oracle"—an entity unspecified by Turing "apart from saying that it cannot be a machine" (Turing (1939)).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The model of computation that Turing called his "universal machine"—"**U**" for short—is considered by some to have been the fundamental theoretical breakthrough that led to the notion of the stored-program computer.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In terms of computational complexity, a multi-tape universal Turing machine need only be slower by logarithmic factor compared to the machines it simulates.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Turing machines are more powerful than some other kinds of automata, such as finite-state machines and pushdown automata.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] According to the Church–Turing thesis, they are as powerful as real machines, and are able to execute any operation that a real program can.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] What is neglected in this statement is that, because a real machine can only have a finite number of *configurations*, it is nothing but a finite-state machine, whereas a Turing machine has an unlimited amount of storage space available for its computations.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] A limitation of Turing machines is that they do not model the strengths of a particular arrangement well.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] For instance, modern stored-program computers are actually instances of a more specific form of abstract machine known as the random-access stored-program machine or RASP machine model.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Like the universal Turing machine, the RASP stores its "program" in "memory" external to its finite-state machine's "instructions".
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Unlike the universal Turing machine, the RASP has an infinite number of distinguishable, numbered but unbounded "registers"—memory "cells" that can contain any integer (cf.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Elgot and Robinson (1964), Hartmanis (1971), and in particular Cook-Rechow (1973); references at random-access machine).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The RASP's finite-state machine is equipped with the capability for indirect addressing (e.g., the contents of one register can be used as an address to specify another register); thus the RASP's "program" can address any register in the register-sequence.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] An example of this is binary search, an algorithm that can be shown to perform more quickly when using the RASP model of computation rather than the Turing machine model.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In the early days of computing, computer use was typically limited to batch processing, i.e., non-interactive tasks, each producing output data from given input data.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Computability theory, which studies computability of functions from inputs to outputs, and for which Turing machines were invented, reflects this practice.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Since the 1970s, interactive use of computers became much more common.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In principle, it is possible to model this by having an external agent read from the tape and write to it at the same time as a Turing machine, but this rarely matches how interaction actually happens; therefore, when describing interactivity, alternatives such as I/O automata are usually preferred.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Some algorithms run in polynomial time in one model but not in the other one.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] However, if an algorithm runs in polynomial time in the arithmetic model, and in addition, the binary length of all involved numbers is polynomial in the length of the input, then it is always polynomial-time in the Turing model.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Such an algorithm is said to run in strongly polynomial time.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Gandy's analysis of Babbage's analytical engine describes the following five operations (cf. p.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Any sequence of operations is an operation.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Iteration of an operation (repeating n times an operation P).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Conditional iteration (repeating n times an operation P conditional on the "success" of test T).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Conditional transfer (i.e., conditional "goto").
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] With regard to Hilbert's problems posed by the famous mathematician David Hilbert in 1900, an aspect of problem #10 had been floating about for almost 30 years before it was framed precisely.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] By 1922, this notion of "Entscheidungsproblem" had developed a bit, and H.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] By the 1928 international congress of mathematicians, Hilbert "made his questions quite precise.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Second, was mathematics *consistent* ...
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] And thirdly, was mathematics *decidable*?" The first two questions were answered in 1930 by Kurt Gödel at the very same meeting where Hilbert delivered his retirement speech (much to the chagrin of Hilbert); the third—the Entscheidungsproblem—had to wait until the mid-1930s.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] The problem was that an answer first required a precise definition of "definite general applicable prescription", which Princeton professor Alonzo Church would come to call "effective calculability", and in 1928 no such definition existed.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] But over the next 6–7 years Emil Post developed his definition of a worker moving from room to room writing and erasing marks per a list of instructions, as did Church and his two students Stephen Kleene and J.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Rosser by use of Church's lambda-calculus and Gödel's recursion theory (1934).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Church's paper (published 15 April 1936) showed that the Entscheidungsproblem was indeed "undecidable" and beat Turing to the punch by almost a year (Turing's paper submitted 28 May 1936, published January 1937).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In the meantime, Emil Post submitted a brief paper in the fall of 1936, so Turing at least had priority over Post.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] While Church refereed Turing's paper, Turing had time to study Church's paper and add an Appendix where he sketched a proof that Church's lambda-calculus and his machines would compute the same functions.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Post had only proposed a definition of calculability and criticised Church's "definition", but had proved nothing.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In the spring of 1935, Turing as a young Master's student at King's College, Cambridge, took on the challenge; he had been stimulated by the lectures of the logician M.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Newman "and learned from them of Gödel's work and the Entscheidungsproblem ...
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] While Gandy believed that Newman's statement above is "misleading", this opinion is not shared by all.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Turing had a lifelong interest in machines: "Alan had dreamt of inventing typewriters as a boy; [his mother] Mrs.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Turing had a typewriter; and he could well have begun by asking himself what was meant by calling a typewriter 'mechanical'" (Hodges p.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] While at Princeton pursuing his PhD, Turing built a Boolean-logic multiplier (see below).
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Alan Turing invented the "a-machine" (automatic machine) in 1936.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Turing submitted his paper on 31 May 1936 to the London Mathematical Society for its *Proceedings*, but it was published in early 1937 and offprints were available in February 1937.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Thus by providing a mathematical description of a very simple device capable of arbitrary computations, he was able to prove properties of computation in general—and in particular, the uncomputability of the *Entscheidungsproblem* ('decision problem').
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Arguments still continue concerning the origin and nature of what has been named by Kleene (1952) Turing's Thesis.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] — from Turing's paper as reprinted in *The Undecidable*, p.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Turing's example (his second proof): If one is to ask for a general procedure to tell us: "Does this machine ever print 0", the question is "undecidable".
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] In 1937, while at Princeton working on his PhD thesis, Turing built a digital (Boolean-logic) multiplier from scratch, making his own electromechanical relays (Hodges p.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] "Alan's task was to embody the logical design of a Turing machine in a network of relay-operated switches ..." (Hodges p.
[src:automata-formal-languages/turing-machine] Today, the counter, register and random-access machines and their sire the Turing machine continue to be the models of choice for theorists investigating questions in the theory of computation.
